<TITLE> England could rotate players says ECB chairman </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Dec 12 (bdnews.com/Reuters) - England could rotate their international players in order to keep them fresh, the new chairman of the England and Wales Cricket Board said. "We're heading towards rotation, more specialists and different sides put out in different forms of the game and against different types of opposition," Giles Clarke told the January issue of The Wisden Cricketer magazine. "It's not unreasonable to consider that England could field some highly effective XIs against some of the test sides." For several years England have dallied with the concept of separate sides for tests and one-day internationals with little success as they have performed generally poorly in the short-form of the game. When it was put to Clarke that English cricket lacked the depth to follow such a course of action, he replied: "That's a perfectly legitimate comment but all I can say is we're going to have to." Clarke told the BBC: "We have had feedback from players that there are times when they need a rest. "Rotation is a part of sport. If you go and watch any Premier League football match, there's a lot of rotation." Clarke's comments appear to contradict the findings of the Schofield Report, which recommended a reduction in the amount of cricket played. "Everyone recognises we have to fund the game," Clarke said. "And funding is increasingly about academies and bigger grounds and if we are going to have bigger grounds, then we have to give them games to stag
